{"cursor":"9297","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox language family |name=Hindi |altname= (regional languages of the Hindi\narea) |region=Hindi Belt, South Asia |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=Indo-\nIranian |fam3=Indo-Aryan |child1= Western Hindi (partial) |child2= Eastern Hindi\n(partial) |child3= Bihari (partial) |child4= Pahari (partial) |child5=\nRajasthani |map=Hindi belt.png |mapcaption=The Hindi belt }}\n\n'Hindi', in the broad sense, is a dialect continuum within the Indo-Aryan\nlanguage family in the northern plains of India, in what may be described as the\n'Hindi Belt'. In the words of Masica (1991), these are the so-called regional\nlanguages of the Hindi area, sometimes less accurately called Hindi \"dialects\".\nHindi in this sense is an ethnic rather than a linguistic concept.\n\nThis broad definition of Hind is the one used in the Indian census and results\nin a clear majority of Indians being speakers of Hindi, though Hindi-area\nrespondents vary as to whether they call their language Hindi or use a local\nlanguage name. As defined in the 1991 census, Hindi has a broad and a narrow\nsense; the broad sense covers a number of Central, East-Central, Eastern, and\nNorthern Zone languages, including the Bihari languages except Maithili, all the\nRajasthani languages, and the Pahari languages except Dogri and Nepali. This is\nan area bounded on the northwest by Punjabi, on the west by Sindhi, on the south\nby Gujarati, Marathi and Oriya; on the east by Maithili and Bengali; and on the\nnorth by Nepali. Linguistically, the varieties of this area can be considered\nseparate languages rather than dialects of a single language.\n\nThe name \"Hindi\" is thus ambiguous. The Hindi languages proper are Hindi in a\nnarrower sense, which can be equated with the Central Zone Indic languages. They\nare conventionally divided into Western Hindi and Eastern Hindi. An even\nnarrower definition of Hindi is that of Modern Standard Hindi, or Manak Hindi, a\nstandardised register of Hindustani. Standardised Hindustaniâthat is, Manak\nHindi and Urduâis historically based on the Khariboli dialect of 17th-century\nDelhi, a Western Hindi dialect.\n","linknr":469,"url":"Hindi_language_(generic)","recorded":1375069284,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hindi_language_(Hindi_belt)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hindi_language_(Hindi_belt)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Hindi_language_(Hindi_belt)","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Hindi_language_(generic)&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Modern_Standard_Hindi","/wiki/Hindi_languages","/wiki/Hindi_Belt","/wiki/South_Asia","/wiki/Language_family","/wiki/Indo-European_languages","/wiki/Indo-Iranian_languages","/wiki/Indo-Aryan_languages","/wiki/Western_Hindi","/wiki/Eastern_Hindi","/wiki/Bihari_languages","/wiki/Pahari_languages","/wiki/Rajasthani_language","/wiki/File:Hindi_belt.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Hindi_belt.png/300px-Hindi_belt.png","/wiki/Hindi_belt","/wiki/Dialect_continuum","/wiki/Indo-Aryan_languages","/wiki/Hindi_Belt","/wiki/Indian_census","/wiki/Demographics_of_India","/wiki/Central_Indo-Aryan_languages","/wiki/East_Central_Indo-Aryan_languages","/wiki/List_of_Ea